  :key-finding
    (:name "Motoi cons vs R5RS cons semantics"
     :description "Motoi's `cons` produces proper lists rather than dotted pairs.
                   (cons 'a 5) yields ('a 5), not ('a . 5). Consequently
                   (cdr (cons 'a 5)) yields (5) — a length-1 list — not the
                   atom 5. Wave 1's Book of ML used the R7RS convention
                   (cdr entry to get the value), which SILENTLY produced
                   single-element-list wrapped values. This propagated into
                   Wave 1 Ch 16's cache-lookup and Ch 11's tok->id lookup and
                   Ch 2's cosine-similarity example. The bug hid because
                   Motoi's arithmetic coerces (5) to 5 in many contexts."
     :impact "Wave 1 was 'shipped verified' but many capstones would have
              failed if a reader typed them into the REPL. Wave 2 discovered
              this while gradient-checking the Ch 16 backward pass — analytic
              gradients disagreed with finite-difference by orders of
              magnitude. Trace revealed cache-get was returning
              wrapped-in-list values."
     :fix "Two patterns. (1) For alists: build with `(list 'key value)`
           rather than `(cons 'key value)`; read with `cadr`. (2) The Motoi
           `cadr` accessor unwraps consistently whether value is atomic or
           list."
     :recommendation "The cons semantic is DOCUMENTED in the Motoi reference
                      but not called out for authoring. Add to
                      MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat as a common-mistakes
                      note; add to Book of R7RS Recipes ch3 (records/alists);
                      no runtime change needed, this is a doctrine
                      correction not a bug.")
